Chesser handles deeply nested subvariations, indicating depth with tabs.

{(2...Nc6 3.d4 exd4 (3...d6 4.Nc3 Nf6 (4...exd4 5.Nxd4 Nf6 (5...Nxd4 6.Qxd4)  (5... Be7 6.Bf4) 6.Bb5)))} ➡️

(2...Nc6 3.d4 exd4 (3...d6 4.Nc3 Nf6 (4...exd4 5.Nxd4 Nf6 (5...Nxd4 6.Qxd4)  (5... Be7 6.Bf4) 6.Bb5 {stepping down ↙️}) {stepping down ↙️}) {stepping down ↙️ (these comments included for illustration only...)}

Black has now an opportunity to take the initiative that should not be wasted.

(4...Bc5 {(Classical Variation) attacks White's central Knight on d4 and forces White to either move it or protect it. Black should expect replies like} 5.Be3{,} 5.Nxc6{, or} 5.Nb3).

(4...Nf6) {(Schmidt Variation) is a common alternative. Black puts immediate attacking pressure on White's e-pawn.}

(4...Qh4) {(Steinitz Variation) is more aggressive. Black immediately attempts to win White's e-pawn outright and indeed can practically win it by force. However, doing so costs time and White is thought to get more than enough compensation after:}

(4...Qh4 5.Nc3 Bb4 6.Be2 Qxe4 7.Nb5 Bxc3+ 8.bxc3 Kd8 9.O-O)

White develops the bishop to a good square where it controls a valuable diagonal. From c4 the Bishop controls d5 and pressures Black's f7-pawn, the most vulnerable pawn in Black's position. Having developed both their kingside minor pieces quickly, White is ready to castle. White's plans include a swift attack on f7 and building a strong center with c3 and d4.

There is no immediate threat to Black's position so they have some flexibility in how to respond. It would be good to develop a piece, and there are several options, the top two being (3...Nf6), the Two Knights, or (3...Bc5), the Giuoco Piano, which reflects a choice of whether to keep or to release control of g5.

